Video streaming challengesÂ 
Â 
Content Delivery Network (CDN) plays an important role in the video streamin g ecosystem. ItÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 3

provides the backbone infrastructure to deliver the video streams to the end viewers. OneÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
major limitation of todayâ€™s CDN networks is the so-called â€‹â€œlast-mileâ€ delivery problemâ€‹.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
Typically, the CDN providers build data centers called Point-of-Presences (POPs) â€‹in manyÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
locations around the world, with the hope that these POPs are geographically close to theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewers. However, the number of POPs are limited, hence cannot be close enough to manyÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewers, especially in less economically developed regions. This â€œlast-mileâ€ link is usually theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
bottleneck of the streaming delivery pipeline and often leads to undesirable user experienceÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
including choppy streams and frequent rebuffering.Â 
Â 
To the streaming sites, another major concern is the CDN bandwidth cost. For popular sites,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the CDN bandwidth cost can easily go up to tens of millions of dollars per year. Even ifÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
platforms own proprietary CDNs, maintenance costs are often high.Â 
Â 
These issues are becoming even more prominent with the coming era of 4K, 360Â° VRÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
streaming, and upcoming technologies such as light field streaming. Table 1 compares theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
bandwidth requirement of todayâ€™s mainstream 720p/HD stream with 4K, 360Â° VR and futureÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
lightfield streams. It is clear that the bandwidth requirement increases by orders of magnitude.Â 
