To solve the VR and light field video delivery problem, the industry has started to exploreÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
â€œâ€‹foveated streamingâ€‹â€ technology. Instead of streaming the entire video in full resolution, thisÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
technology reduces the image quality in the peripheral vision (outside of the zone gazed by theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
fovea) in order to reduce bandwidth requirement. As the viewer turns his or her head to look atÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
a different direction, the system adapts the spatial video resolution accordingly by fetching theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
high resolution video packets for the viewing direction from the server. For the foveatedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
streaming technology to work well in practice, the round-trip time between the server and theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewer has to be small enough. For the viewers that are geographically far away for the CDNÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
POPs, their VR stream viewing experience will be compromised even with foveated streamingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
technology.Â 

