publish their video streams to the â€‹ingest nodesâ€‹. â€‹Ingest nodes run on computers contributed byÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the user community. The ingest nodes are responsible for transcoding the video stream toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
different bitrates and resolutions. Then, the â€‹caching nodes pull the video streams and relay toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
end viewers. Any user can contribute his or her computer as a caching node by running aÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
special video caching software client we are developing. The video caching software isÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
responsible for choosing the upstream node, and relaying the video stream to the downstreamÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
nodes. This is similar to traditional P2P file sharing systems like BitTorrent, but with anÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
important extra constraint on latency due to the realtime nature of live streaming. Rather thanÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
sending chunks of a file out-of-order as in P2P file sharing systems, more urgent high-priorityÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
packets will be sent first. Furthermore, to minimize re-buffering, each caching node may cacheÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the entire video file instead of storing only a portion of a file as P2P file sharing systems do.Â 
Â 
For ease of explanation, the viewer nodes and the caching nodes are drawn as separatedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
nodes in Figure 3. However, it is worth pointing out that in practice, a user can run both theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
caching software and viewer software on the same computer.Â 
Â 
Figure 3 Right shows the DSN architecture for â€‹video on demandâ€‹. Compared to live streaming,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the only difference is that the â€‹influencers â€‹(aka â€‹content creatorsâ€‹) upload the source video file toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

10Â 



a â€‹storage system â€‹for later retrieval, rather than publishing the stream to the ingest nodes. TheÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
storage system can be a decentralized file system such as IPFS or SWARM , or cloud-basedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 9 10

storage like AWS S3. The rest of the network is essentially the same as in the live streamingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
scenario.Â 
Â 
For any viewer and caching node to receive a stream with high quality and low latency, itsÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
physical proximity to their peer caching nodes is essential. Thus, when a new node joins theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
DSN network, it goes through a bootstrapping process to discover the caching nodes that areÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
physically nearby. P2P file sharing systems typically employ Distributed Hash Table (DHT) suchÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
as Kademlia to find peer nodes. In Kademlia, each node is assigned a random GUID, and theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
distance between the two nodes is calculated as the XOR of their GUIDs. While this distanceÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
measure is sufficient for non-realtime applications such as file sharing, in the context of videoÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
streaming, it is important for the nodes to identify peering nodes that are geographically close.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
To achieve this, we propose to encode the geographic information into the GUID as shownÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
belowÂ 
Â 

UID QuadtreeRegionID || RandomBitsPostf ixG =  Â 
Â 

Â 
The GUID is the concatenation of two parts. The first part is the â€‹QuadtreeRegionIDâ€‹, a 64 bitÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
long string that encodes the geographical region of the caching node. The Quadtree dataÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
structure is employed as the spatial index. The second part is a 32 bit random bit postfix toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
differentiate caching nodes in the same quadtree region. This way the XOR of two GUIDs is aÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
rough estimation of the geographical distance between two nodes. Thus a new node can firstÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
collect a list of candidate peer nodes with small GUID XOR distances. Then, it can send a pingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
request to the candidates to measure the actual round trip time.Â 

Â 

