The Theta BlockchainÂ 

OverviewÂ 
Â 
The Theta blockchain is similar to the Bitcoin blockchain in many ways. Caching nodes are theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 12

miners for the Theta blockchain. The Theta network implements a transaction ledger via aÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
blockchain. Each block consists of a set of transactions of Theta tokens. To add a new block toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the blockchain, a miner needs to validate the transactions and solve a Proof-of-Work basedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
cryptographic hash puzzle. The Proof-of-Work parameter is dynamically adjusted so that oneÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
block is added to the chain in a roughly fixed amount of time, similar to Bitcoin. Furthermore, asÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
many other blockchains, a caching miner node should consider a transaction as committedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
after a sequence of valid blocks have been added after his block.Â 
Â 
The Theta blockchain also introduces three novel concepts: â€‹1) Reputation Dependent Mining,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
2) Global Reputation Consensus, and 3) Proof-of-Engagement. Below we will discuss each ofÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
these concepts in detail.Â 

Â 

Reputation Dependent MiningÂ 
Â 
The caching nodes in the DSN are the miners for the Theta blockchain. They validateÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
transactions and attempt to add new blocks to the blockchain by solving a Proof-of-WorkÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
(PoW) hash puzzle. However, for the DSN to function properly, in addition to puzzle solving, theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
caching nodes need to relay video streams to end viewers.Â Â 
Â 
In order to incentivize them to relay the video stream, in the Theta protocol, the mining rewardÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
of a block depends on the â€‹reputation scoreâ€‹ of the caching node that mined the block:Â 
Â 

eward (1 r)  r =  +  Â· rewardbase Â   â€‹                              â€‹(2)Â 
Â 
Here â€‹rewardâ€‹base is a predefined constant shared by all the caching nodes. And â€‹r is theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
reputation score, which is a real number between 0 and 1. â€‹Hence, a caching node with a higherÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
reputation score would have a higher block rewardâ€‹. The reputation score of a caching nodeÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
characterizes the contribution of the caching node to the streaming ecosystem. Essentially, aÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
caching node that â€‹relays more video streams â€‹more recentlyâ€‹ â€‹will have a higher reputation score.Â Â 
Â 
The reputation score of a caching node is calculated based on the â€‹service certificates it collectsÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
from its downstream nodes. The concept of â€œservice certificateâ€ is inspired by the â€œpooledÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
miningâ€ approach . In pooled mining, the miners submit â€œnear-miss solutionsâ€ to the masterÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 13 14

on a regular basis to prove that they are constantly trying to solve the PoW mining puzzle forÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the master. In the Theta network, as a caching node relays the video stream to its downstreamÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewers, it will ask its viewers to solve a â€œservice certificate PoW puzzleâ€ and return their puzzleÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
solutions. â€‹These puzzle solutions are the service certificates which prove that the cachingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

12 â€‹Nakamotoâ€‹, Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash SystemÂ 
13 â€‹Luu et alâ€‹. SMARTPOOL: Practical Decentralized Pooled MiningÂ 
14 https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/P2PoolÂ 

16Â 



node has provided service to the viewers for a certain amount of timeâ€‹. If a viewer fails toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
provide the puzzle solutions, the caching node can choose to terminate the stream. When theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
streaming session ends, the viewer simply stops puzzle solving. In other words, â€‹the viewersÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
offer their computational power in exchange for the video stream relay serviceâ€‹.Â 
Â 
The â€‹service certificate PoW puzzleâ€‹ is formally defined as the following minimization problem:Â 
Â 

