One interesting property of the function â€‹fâ€‹(â€‹Tâ€‹totalâ€‹) is that if the parameter ğ›½ is chosen properly â€‹itÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
actually discourages malicious miners from making fake service certificates. In the Appendix,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
we will show that if ğ›½ is proportional to the total network hashing power (similar to BitcoinÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
where the difficulty level of the mining puzzle scales with the total hashing power), forgingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
service certificates actually â€‹reduces the expected mining reward. Intuitively, to forge serviceÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
certificates, a malicious miner needs to spend hashing power. As a result, its chance of miningÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the next block reduces. Even though the fake service certificates it generated can increaseÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
block reward, but with properly chosen ğ›½, the expected mining reward per unit time â€‹strictlyÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
reduces. Thus, a rational miner would not try to forge service certificates.Â 
Â 
We would like to emphasize again that Formula (9) should only account for the serviceÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
certificates generated in the recent time window. The reason that we account for â€‹recency isÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
two-fold: Firstly, this encourages the caching nodes to keep relaying the video streams. ItÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
cannot simply rely on the video relaying work done in the distant past to obtain high reputationÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
score. Since a caching miner node cannot predict when it will mine the next block, it will beÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
always motivated to relay the video streams and collect the service certificates. Secondly, itÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
reduces the amount of service certificates that need to be validated by other caching minerÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
nodes. This, in turn, reduces the bandwidth overhead of the Theta protocol.Â 

18Â 



Â 
To determine whether a service certificate is generated in the defined time window, one canÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
