Â 
Support For Pooled MiningÂ 

Â 
Pooled mining  is a mining approach where multiple miners contribute to the generation of aÂ 15

block, and then split the block reward according to the contributed hashing power. PooledÂ 
mining effectively reduces the variance of mining reward for the participant miners.Â 
Â 
On the Theta blockchain, miners can also form pools. Similar to Bitcoin mining pools, the minersÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
solve the PoW mining puzzle on behalf of the master. In addition, their downstream viewersÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
generate the service certificates for the master, by using the public key of the master as â€‹pkâ€‹i inÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the service certificate PoW puzzle given by Formula (3).Â 
Â 
Â 
Â 
Â 

15 https://en.bitcoin.it/wiki/Pooled_miningÂ 

20Â 



However, pooled mining presents two unique challenges to the Theta blockchain:Â 
Â 
â— First, the number of service certificates for each block could potentially be large, sinceÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

a pool can serve many viewers. Including all the certificates in the block body mayÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
result in considerable bandwidth and storage overhead.Â 

Â 
â— Second, it is worth noting that on the Theta blockchain, pooling not only reducesÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

reward variance, but also increases the expected mining reward, since the pool canÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
collectively serves more viewers than an individual caching miner node. Hence,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
compared to other cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin, this would provide extra incentive forÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the miners to form big pools and potentially lead to centralization of power.Â 

Â 
To address these challenges, we propose the following techniques.Â 
Â 
Â 
Â 

TECHNIQUE 1 â€‹:Â 

Limit the total number of service certificates per blockÂ 
Â 
The protocol can limit the total number of service certificates per block. This has twoÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
advantages.Â Â 
Â 
Firstly, this places an upper bound on the additional storage space required for the serviceÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
certificates per block. The storage and bandwidth overhead of the protocol are limited andÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
more predictable.Â 
Â 
Secondly, after the limit is reached, the expected block mining reward would not increase withÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
more mining nodes joining the pool. Hence there is no extra incentive for the miners to form bigÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
pools compared to other cryptocurrencies.Â 
Â 
Â 
Â 

TECHNIQUE 2 â€‹:Â 

Less frequent service certificate PoW puzzle changesÂ 
Â 
Earlier in the whitepaper we proposed to have the caching node send a new service certificateÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
PoW puzzle to its viewers each time a new block is confirmed, where the â€‹block_hashâ€‹kÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
parameter in the new puzzle points to the newly confirmed block. Consider a scenario whereÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewer node â€‹j pulls video stream from caching node â€‹i continuously for a couple hours straight.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
Each time a new block is added, viewer node â€‹j needs to generate a different service certificate.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
To reduce the certificate storage overhead, node â€‹i could instead only change the puzzle forÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
every â€‹d > 1 blocks. Figure 8 illustrates the case where â€‹d = 3. For a given â€‹dâ€‹, the expected serviceÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
time for a given service certificate should be calculated using the following FormulaÂ 
Â 

T  in(E[n | H ] / s, d )   sc = m *  Â· T b Â                     â€‹(11)Â 
Â 

