Live Stream Watching RewardÂ 

Proof-of-EngagementÂ 
Â 
Engagement reward is proven to be a very effective way to increase user retention in the liveÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
streaming industry. Examples include daily logins rewarded with virtual currency common inÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
many mobile games and apps.Â 
Â 
In the game streaming context, Twitch recently introduced the â€œTwitch Dropâ€ feature whichÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
randomly rewards the viewers with in-game loot as they watch streams on Twitch.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 18

Engagement reward is also effective for an advertiser to directly target end viewers. In theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
â€œTwitch Dropâ€ example, the rewarded in-game loot provides incentives for the viewers to comeÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
back and play the game, thus effectively retargeting the viewer on behalf of the gameÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
publisher, which can also be viewed as the advertiser sponsoring the stream.Â 
Â 
SLIVER.tvâ€™s Watch & Win platform is another example of a system that rewards viewers forÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
watching the eSports streams. Analytical data shows that the watching incentive increasesÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewer engagement and retention.Â 
Â 
However, these types of engagement reward schemes are usually vulnerable to attacks. ForÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
example, a malicious user can perform the Sybil attack where he or she creates a large numberÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
of accounts to claim engagement rewards. Below we will propose an engagement incentiveÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
protocol based on â€‹Proof-of-Work that increases the robustness of the system against theseÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
attacks.Â 
Â 
In our proposed protocol, for viewers to claim Theta token rewards from advertisers, they willÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
need to solve cryptographic puzzles during the live stream similar to the Bitcoin mining puzzles.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
However, in this case, the Theta rewards is not mined. Instead, the advertisers prepare theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
puzzles and assign the amount of Theta token rewards to each puzzle. The puzzles areÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
embedded â€‹in the live stream itself and sent to viewers continuously during the live broadcastÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
session. The first viewer that solves a puzzle will write the solution to the blockchain and thenÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
receive the corresponding reward after the solution is verified.Â 

Â 

Â 
Figure 11. The ingest server provided by the streaming site embeds cryptographic puzzles intoÂ 

the video stream and sends the modified stream to the CDN.Â 

18 https://dev.twitch.tv/dropsÂ 

27Â 



Â 
The node at the bottom-left corner of the Figure 11 represents the influencer. He or she simplyÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
publishes the stream to the ingest node as usual. As discussed earlier, the ingest node isÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
responsible for transcoding the source stream into â€‹video segments â€‹and then sending them toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the CDN network.Â 
Â 
Besides transcoding, the ingest server will also create a â€‹cryptographic puzzle â€‹similar to theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
Bitcoin mining puzzle â€‹for each video segmentâ€‹. The puzzle is â€œembeddedâ€ in the correspondingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
video segment. To create the puzzle, the ingest server appends a short string to to the end ofÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
each video segment as shown in Figure 8. The short string for â€‹segmentâ€‹m has the followingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
components:Â 

prize , dif f iculty , randstr )  ( m  m  m Â Â      â€‹(12)Â 
Â 

prizeâ€‹m specifies the amount of Theta tokens for solving the puzzle. â€‹difficultyâ€‹m defines theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
difficulty target. â€‹randstrâ€‹m is a short random string (e.g. 128 bits) generated by the ingest serverÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
on the fly. The puzzle here is to find a â€‹nonce â€‹such that the following hash value is smaller thanÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â   Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the maximum possible hash value â€‹Mâ€‹ divided by the difficulty target:Â 
Â 

                â€‹(13)ASH(segment  || randstr  || pk || nonce) M  / dif f iculty  H m m â‰¤  m Â 
Â 
In the above formula â€‹pkâ€‹ is the public key of the viewer node.Â 
Â 
For each puzzle, only the first node that provides the solution can win the prize. As mentionedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
earlier, the issuance of the puzzle prizes are carried out using a smart incentive contract. If aÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
node solves a puzzle, it sends the solution to the incentive contract immediately in order toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
claim the prize. For the incentive contract to verify the solutions of the puzzles, the advertisersÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
and/or the viewers can save the puzzles (segment plus the short string postfix) toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
decentralized storage system such as IPFS/SWARM. Upon validation of each puzzle solution,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the incentive contract generates the transaction to send the prize to the viewer.Â Â 
Â 
The parameter â€‹difficultyâ€‹m controls the expected amount of time a viewer node needs to solveÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the puzzle similar to Bitcoin mining. It should not be too easy so a viewer node can solve it inÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
milliseconds -- this will create an unfair advantage for the nodes that has lower streamingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
latency. Likewise, it should not be too hard otherwise it takes too much computing time to findÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the solution, which may discourage viewers from participating.Â 
Â 
The prize of each puzzle is determined by the streaming site, so â€‹the streaming site has fullÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
control of the total budgetâ€‹. The streaming site can choose prizes wisely so it encourages theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewers to watch the stream but keeps the total cost under budget.Â 
Â 
It is worth noting that in Formula (13), the video segment â€‹segmentâ€‹m is required in order for theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewer nodes to compute the hash. This means the viewer has to â€œwatchâ€ the video segmentÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
to win the prize. To encourage viewers to watch the entire stream, â€‹the prizes for the segmentsÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
can increase monotonically with timeâ€‹. Then, it can be proven that for viewers, the optimalÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
strategy to maximize its expected total reward is to pull each video segment and try to solveÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
each of the puzzles.Â 
Â 
The puzzles might create overhead for the stream delivery. However, the total number of bitsÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
of the additional string (â€‹prizeâ€‹mâ€‹, â€‹difficultyâ€‹mâ€‹, â€‹randstrâ€‹mâ€‹) is small enough so the overhead for streamÂ  Â  Â  Â   Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
delivery is negligible. Typically a video segment is roughly 1 Mbits, whereas the additional stringÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
is less than 512 bits. The overhead is only around 0.05%.Â 
Â 

28Â 



In the discussion above, we only attach a single puzzle to one segment. In practice, we canÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
attach multiple puzzles to each segment to increase the number of rewarded viewers for theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
live streams. The overhead should still be negligible.Â 
Â 
In short, it is worth noting that Proof-of-Engagement is a probabilistic proof that a certainÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
number of viewers have watched the video stream. This proof is publicly auditable, unlikeÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
todayâ€™s streaming ecosystem, such data is only available to streaming sites. In this case, itÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
greatly improves transparency to advertisers.Â 

ExtensionsÂ 
Â 
The incentive protocol proposed above embeds the cryptographic puzzles into the videoÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
streams to encourage viewers to watch the streams. This idea can be extended to provideÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
other types of user engagement rewards. For example, many website and apps use â€œdailyÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
loginâ€ reward to encourage users to come back to the site. We can assign a cryptographicÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
puzzle each day a user logs in, and the user gets the reward if he or she can provide theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
solution. Following the same line of reasoning above, the cryptographic puzzles can discourageÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the user from creating multiple accounts to loot daily rewards.Â 
Â 
Furthermore, introduce smart contracts among the leaf nodes to solve a specific puzzleÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
together. If any of the leaf nodes in the contract solves the puzzle, the prize will be dividedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
among the participants. This will further increase the number of rewarded viewers for the liveÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
streams, and shorten the expected amount of time to get the first reward for the participatingÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
viewers.Â 
Â 
One shortcoming with the Proof-of-Work based Proof-of-Engagement scheme is that itÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
consumes computing resource on the viewerâ€™s computer to solve the cryptographic puzzles. InÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
practice, we can allow the viewers to tune the amount of CPU/GPU usage for puzzle solving, soÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the puzzle solving will not overtax their computer resources.Â 
Â 
An alternative approach to address the computation overhead concern is to devise stake basedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
Proof-of-Engagement instead of work based. In the Appendix we will give details of a stakeÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
based Proof-of-Engagement scheme and discuss the pros and cons compared to work basedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
Proof-of-Engagement.Â 

Anti-Fraud ConsiderationsÂ Â 
Â 

â— For the live stream watching reward, the cryptographic Proof-of-Work prevents falseÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
claims for prizes from the viewers. On the other hand, if the advertiser cheats (e.g.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
save incorrect puzzles to storage), its credibility quickly and transparently collapses,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
and other honest competing advertisers will earn the trust from viewers.Â 

Â 
â— Sybil Attackâ€‹: It is worth noting that our proposed protocol greatly improves theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

resistance to Sybil attack. A malicious user might create thousands of nodes on aÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
computer, but â€‹since these nodes share the same computing resource, the probability thatÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the user finds the puzzle solution doesnâ€™t increaseâ€‹. A professional attacker might gather aÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
large amount of computing resources to solve the puzzles, however, as we mentionedÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
earlier, â€‹the prizes for the puzzles are determined by the streaming siteâ€‹. It is possibleÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
to choose the prizes such that the payout for the professional attacker is below his orÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
her investment in computing resources therefore making it economically unprofitable.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
Nonetheless, the prizes are still attractive to all legitimate viewers -- after all, they areÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

29Â 



simply using redundant computing resources to solve the puzzles while they view theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
live-stream of interest, so end viewers lose nothing and only stand to gain.Â 

Â 

Future WorkÂ 
Â 
In this whitepaper, we introduced a new Decentralized Streaming Network (DSN) and the ThetaÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
protocol, a new blockchain and token as the incentive mechanism for the DSN. The ThetaÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
network encourages viewers to share their memory and bandwidth resources and solves aÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
number of technical and business challenges. The launch of the native Theta network isÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
planned for late 2018.Â 
Â 
In the initial phase, we have assumed the video and livestream to be ad-supported freeÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
content. The next phase of our research will provide support for premium paid content, piracyÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
issues and anti-piracy mechanisms in a trustless environment.Â Â 
Â 
Â 
There are many other technical aspects of the protocol and network which we classify asÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
future work, beyond the initial launch of the native Theta network:Â 
Â 

â— Shared Mining Rewardsâ€‹. Smart Contracts in the form of incentive contracts can beÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
used to distribute mining rewards between different parties. This would allow certainÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
servers to incentivize end viewers to watch their stream, separate from advertiserâ€™sÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
rewards for viewers, and to reward streamers for providing their content to the miner.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
This may be coordinated with the reputation system such that as more rewards areÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
distributed, the better the chances of miners getting the rewards.Â Â 

Â 
â— Anti-Piracyâ€‹. â€‹The network can be expanded to include anti-piracy - since tokens mayÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

be used to stream and cache certain content, the tokens serve as a â€œdis-incentiveâ€Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
within the network as the content can be tagged as required tokens or â€œpremiumÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
contentâ€.Â 

Â 
â— General Purpose Service Platformâ€‹. The reputation dependent mining protocol is inÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

fact independent of streaming. It can be extended to handle other types of service toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
allow end users to receive service for free. Another interesting extension is to supportÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
more general types of smart contracts in addition to the smart streaming contracts. InÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the extreme case, the smart contracts supported could be Turing complete similar toÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
the Ethereum Smart Contract . This could enable DApps built on top the ThetaÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 19

blockchain to issue their own tokens.Â 
Â 

â— Combining Proof-of-Stake and Proof-of-Work for Reputation Dependent Miningâ€‹.Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
Proof-of-Stake has the advantage of less electrical power waste and moreÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
eco-friendly. A possible improvement for the reputation dependent mining frameworkÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
is to incorporate Proof-of-Stake. For instance, a viewer can send certain amount ofÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
tokens to the upstream caching node during the streaming session to increase theÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
chance that the upstream caching node generates the next block. The caching nodeÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
returns the same amount of tokens to the viewer after the streaming sessionÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 

19 https://github.com/ethereum/wiki/wiki/White-PaperÂ 

30Â 



(enforced by a smart contract). This way the viewer still gets the video stream for free,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
and yet the expected minting reward of the upstream caching node increases. OneÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
issue with such a scheme is the cold start problem where a new viewer might notÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
have enough tokens. However, this can be solved combining Proof-of-Work styleÂ  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
mining. After the viewer obtains enough initial tokens through Proof-of-Work mining,Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â 
he can get the video streams for free without spending computational power.Â 

Â 

